{"cursor":"40275","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{multiple issues|\n\n\n}}\n\nThe 'Mantria Corporation Ponzi Scheme' has been described as the \"biggest green\nenergy scam\" in United States history. It has gone\nunprosecuted even though a Federal judge found Mantria had scammed more than\n$54.5 million âby egregiously, recklessly, knowingly, and shamelessly\nperpetrating a fraudulent schemeâ that used âmisrepresentations, omissions, and\nblatant lies to induce unsuspecting and unwitting victim investors to liquidate\nthe equity in their homes and take out bank loans to invest in Defendantsâ\nscheme, which was nothing more than smoke and mirrors.â \n\nThe Federal judge took 2 years to rule that Mantria was a Ponzi\nscheme, nearly 3 years for the SEC to get a final\njudgment, more than 3 years have gone by without criminal charges by\nthe DOJ, no money has been returned to any of the victims by the\nReceivership, the IRS has not pursued the theft of 401k\nand health insurance deductions by company executives, the Department of Labor\nhas not held executives liable for employee compensation as required by\nlaw, all while the Ponzi schemers continue raising money and\noperating other businesses.\n\n[http://www.sec.gov/news/press/2009/2009-247.htm On November 16, 2009, the U.S.\nSecurities and Exchange Commission charged four people], including the two\nprincipals of Mantria Corporation, a Bala Cynwyd, Pennsylvania-based company, in\nan alleged $54 million Ponzi scheme that targeted elderly investors and people\nnearing retirement who were seeking environmentally-friendly investments. In a\ncivil lawsuit in Denver federal court, the SEC accused Mantria Corp. and its\nprincipals Troy Wragg and Amanda Knorr of raising $54 million from more than 300\ninvestors nationwide in a dozen fraudulent securities offerings. The SEC said\nMantria enlisted Speed of Wealth LLC, a Centennial, Colorado, company run by the\ntwo other people charged in the case, Wayde and Donna McKelvy, to encourage\ninvestors to liquidate retirement plans and home equity, and buy securities\noffering returns of 17 percent to more than 100 percent annually.\n\nThe SEC said Mantria's environmental initiatives have not generated any\nsignificant cash, and any returns paid to investors have been funded almost\nexclusively from other investors' contributions. The SEC alleges that the\nMcKelvys, who were previously married and living in the Denver area,\nparticularly targeted elderly investors or those approaching retirement age to\nfinance such \"green\" initiatives of Mantria Corporation as a supposed âcarbon\nnegativeâ housing community in rural Tennessee and a âbiocharâ charcoal\nsubstitute made from organic waste. Mantria Corporation operated using 55\ndifferent LLCs.\n","linknr":289,"url":"Mantria_Corporation_Ponzi_Scheme","recorded":1376419910,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Mantria_Corporation_Ponzi_Scheme&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Mantria_Corporation_Ponzi_Scheme&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mantria_Corporation_Ponzi_Scheme","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.visualEditor.viewPageTarget.noscript&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","